to desist. Metellus did not consent when the other plebeian tribunes wanted to set him free.<ref>Cassius Dio, Roman History, 37.50.2-4</ref>\n\nIn 59 BC Metellus Celer and Cato the Younger for a time refused to swear obedience to the agrarian law of Julius Caesar, who was consul in that year. Eventually they complied.<ref>Cassius Dio, Roman History, 38.7.1</ref>\n\nDuring Metellus Celer\u2019s praetorship, [[Titus Labienus]] indicted an old backbench Optimate senator, [[Gaius Rabirius (senator)|Gaius Rabirius]], for the murder of [[Lucius Appuleius Saturninus]] thirty-six years earlier. Saturninus had been opposed by the consuls of the time at the direction of the senate. Thus, with the proposed trial the senate would lose the authority to enforce its decrees. Acts which had received the approval of the senate and had been committed many years earlier tended to give immunity to those who tried to repeat the conduct of Saturninus and make punishment of such acts ineffective. The senate was outraged that an innocent elderly man of senatorial rank was attacked and that the tribunes were entrusted with the control of affairs. There were pro- and anti-prosecution factions. The former won through the support of [[Julius Caesar]], who was the judge together with [[Lucius Julius Caesar (consul 64 BC)|Lucius Julius Caesar]], and Rabirius was charged. The judges had been unlawfully chosen by the urban praetor, [[Publius Cornelius Lentulus Sura|Lentulus Sura]], instead of the people. Rabirius appealed and would have been convicted by the people, but this was prevented by Metellus by obstructing the meeting of the assembly of the people.<ref>Cassius Dio, Roman History, 37.26</ref>\n\nMetellus Celer was married to his cousin [[Claudia Pulchra (wife of Metellus)|Clodia]] Quadrantaria, often referred to in scholarship as Clodia Metelli (\"Clodia the wife of Metellus\"), the daughter of [[Appius Claudius Pulcher (consul 79 BC)|Appius Claudius Pulcher]] and sister of [[Publius Clodius Pulcher]]. They had a daughter named [[Caecilia Metella (daughter of Metellus Celer)|Caecilia Metella]], like all the women in the family of the Caecilii Metelli. Celer's reputation was dogged by the scandals attached to Clodia. A [[Catullus 83|contemporary poem by Catullus]] \"may refer to Celer's marital ineffectiveness and obtuseness\".<ref>Gruen, p. 131.</ref>  The couple were known for their blazing public rows.\n\nQuintus Caecilius Metellus Celer died suddenly in 59 BC--according to some [[poison]]ed by his wife, who was notoriously debauched, reputed to be the incestuous lover of her brother [[Publius Clodius Pulcher|Clodius]], of [[Marcus Caelius Rufus|Caelius]], possibly of the great lyric [[poet]] [[Catullus]] (most authorities identify her as the subject of his ''[[Lesbia]]''), and many others.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Caecilia (gens)]]\n* [[Caecilia Metella (daughter of Metellus Celer)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n;Primary sources\n* Cassius Dio, Roman History, Vol. 3, Books 36-40, Loeb Classical Library, Loeb, 1989; {{ISBN|978-0674990593}}\n* Henry G. Hohn, ''The Life and Letters of Marcus Tullius Cicero'', London, England, 1848, pg. 334.\n* Sallust, Catiline's Conspiracy, The Jugurthine War, Histories, Oxford World's Classics, Oxford University Press, 2010; {{ISBN|978-0192823458}}\n\n\n;Secondary Sources\n* T. P. Wiseman, \"Celer and Nepos\", ''Classical Quarterly'' vol. 1 (1971), p.&nbsp;180\u2014182\n* Peter V. Jones and Kenneth C. Sidwell, ''The World of Rome: an introduction to Roman culture'', [[Cambridge University Press]], 1997, p. 104.\n* Erich S. Gruen, ''The Last Generation of the Roman Republic'', [[University of California Press]], 1995, pp. 58, 130. \n\n<br>\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box|\n title=Consul|\n before=[[Marcus Pupius Piso Frugi Calpurnianus]], <br>[[Marcus Valerius Messalla Niger]]|\n years=60 BC, <br>with [[Lucius Afranius (consul)|Lucius Afranius]] |\n after=[[Julius Caesar]], <br>[[Marcus Calpurnius Bibulus]] |\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caecilius Metellus Celer, Quintus}}\n[[Category:100s BC births]]\n[[Category:59 BC deaths]]\n[[Category:Roman Republican consuls]]\n[[Category:1st-century BC Romans]]\n[[Category:Senators of the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Roman Republican praetors]]\n[[Category:Augurs of the Roman Republic]]\n[[Category:Caecilii|Metellus Celer, Quintus]]\n[[Category:Optimates]]\n", "name_user": "Klbrain", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quintus_Caecilius_Metellus_Celer"}
{"title_page": "2019 Thuringian state election", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name      = 2019 Thuringian state election\n| country            = Thuringia\n| type               = parliamentary\n| ongoing            = no\n| previous_election  = 2014 Thuringian state election\n| previous_year      = 2014\n| next_election      = Next Thuringian state election\n| next_year          = Next\n| seats_for_election = All 90 seats of the [[Landtag of Thuringia]]\n| majority_seats     = 46\n| election_date      = 27 October 2019\n| registered         = 1,729,242 {{decrease}} 4.6%\n| turnout            = 1,121,814 (64.9%)<br>{{increase}} 12.2%\n\n<!-- Linke -->\n| image1         = [[File:2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201357.jpg|150x150px]]\n| leader1        = [[Bodo Ramelow]]\n| party1         = The Left (Germany)\n| last_election1 = 28 seats, 28.2%\n| seats1         = 29\n| seat_change1   = {{increase}} 1\n| popular_vote1  = 343,780\n| percentage1    = 31.0%\n| swing1         = {{increase}} 2.8%\n\n<!-- AfD -->\n| image2         = [[File:2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201388.jpg|150x150px]]\n| leader2        = [[Bj\u00f6rn H\u00f6cke]]\n| party2         = Alternative for Germany\n| last_election2 = 11 seats, 10.6%\n| seats2         = 22\n| seat_change2   = {{increase}} 11\n| popular_vote2  = 259,382\n| percentage2    = 23.4%\n| swing2         = {{increase}} 12.8%\n\n<!-- CDU -->\n| image3         = [[File:2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201393.jpg|150x150px]]\n| leader3        = [[Mike Mohring (politician)|Mike Mohring]]\n| party3         = Christian Democratic Union (Germany)\n| last_election3 = 34 seats, 33.5%\n| seats3         = 21\n| seat_change3   = {{decrease}} 13\n| popular_vote3  = 241,049\n| percentage3    = 21.7%\n| swing3         = {{decrease}} 11.8%\n\n<!-- SPD -->\n| image4         = [[File:2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201364.jpg|150x150px]]\n| leader4        = [[Wolfgang Tiefensee]]\n| party4         = Social Democratic Party of Germany\n| last_election4 = 12 seats, 12.4%\n| seats4         = 8\n| seat_change4   = {{decrease}} 4\n| popular_vote4  = 90,987\n| percentage4    = 8.2%\n| swing4         = {{decrease}} 4.2%\n\n<!-- Gr\u00fcne -->\n| image5         = [[File:2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201369.jpg|75x75px]]<br>[[File:2016-02-25 Dirk Adams by Olaf Kosinsky-1.jpg|75x75px]]\n| leader5        = [[Anja Siegesmund]]<br/>& Dirk Adams\n| party5         = Alliance 90/The Greens\n| last_election5 = 6 seats, 5.7%\n| seats5         = 5\n| seat_change5   = {{decrease}} 1\n| popular_vote5  = 57,474\n| percentage5    = 5.2%\n| swing5         = {{decrease}} 0.5%\n\n<!-- FDP -->\n| image6         = [[File:2019-10-27 Wahlabend Th\u00fcringen by Sandro Halank\u201337.jpg|150x150px]]\n| leader6        = [[Thomas Kemmerich]]\n| party6         = Free Democratic Party (Germany)\n| last_election6 = 0 seats, 2.5%\n| seats6         = 5\n| seat_change6   = {{increase}} 5\n| popular_vote6  = 55,493\n| percentage6    = 5.0%\n| swing6         = {{increase}} 2.5%\n\n<!-- Map -->\n| map_image   = Th\u00fcringen Landtagswahlkarte 2019.svg\n| map_size    = 400px\n| map_caption = Results for the direct mandates.\n\n<!-- Result -->\n| title           = [[List of Ministers-President of Thuringia|Minister-President]]\n| before_election = [[Bodo Ramelow]]\n| before_party    = The Left (Germany)\n| after_election  = [[Thomas Kemmerich]]\n| after_party     = Free Democratic Party (Germany)\n}}\nThe '''2019 Thuringian state election''' was held on 27 October 2019 to elect the members of the 7th [[Landtag of Thuringia]]. The incumbent government was a coalition consisting of [[The Left (Germany)|The Left]], the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]] (SPD), and [[Alliance 90/The Greens|The Greens]], led by [[List of Ministers-President of Thuringia|Minister-President]] [[Bodo Ramelow]]. The Left became the largest party for the first time in any German state, but the election resulted in a [[hung parliament]] as the governing coalition fell 4 seats short of an overall majority. As The Left and the far-right [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) together hold a negative majority, no politically realistic majority government exists.\n\nOn 5 February 2020, the Landtag voted to elect the Minister-President. Ramelow was expected to be re-elected to lead a minority government, since the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] (CDU) declined to run a candidate, and neither the AfD's candidate nor the [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|Free Democratic Party]] (FDP) leader [[Thomas Kemmerich]] were expected to garner enough votes to win. However, on the third ballot, Kemmerich was unexpectedly elected, winning 45 votes to incumbent Ramelow's 44. The votes for Kemmerich came from the FDP, CDU and, controversially, the AfD. This was the first time the AfD had been involved in the election of a head of government in Germany. This was highly controversial, sparking protest throughout both Thuringia and Germany and condemnation from politicians nationwide, including federal Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], who described it as \"unforgivable\".<ref name=\"BBC-8-2-2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51399445|title=Germany AfD: Thuringia PM quits amid fury over far right|publisher=BBC|date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnder intense pressure, Kemmerich announced his resignation just two days later, but remained in office in a caretaker capacity until the Landtag could elect another Minister-President.<ref name=\"BBC-8-2-2020\"></ref> On 4 March, a second vote was held, and Bodo Ramelow was re-elected as Minister-President with the abstentions of the CDU and FDP.<ref name=\"Politico-5-3-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/germanys-thuringia-gets-left-wing-state-premier-in-re-run-vote/|title=Germany\u2019s Thuringia gets left-wing state premier in re-run vote|date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Election date==\nAccording to \u00a7 18 of the ''Thuringian Electoral Law for the Landtag'',<ref>[http://landesrecht.thueringen.de/jportal/portal/t/glw/page/bsthueprod.psml/action/portlets.jw.MainAction?p1=n&eventSubmit_doNavigate=searchInSubtreeTOC&showdoccase=1&doc.hl=0&doc.id=jlr-WahlGTH2012pP18&doc.part=S&toc.poskey=#focuspoint landesrecht.thueringen.de]</ref> the Landtag election must take place on a [[Sunday]] or [[public holiday]] at the earliest 57 months after the beginning of the current parliamentary term on 14 October 2014<ref>Konstituierende Sitzung des 6. Landtags, auf [http://www.thueringer-landtag.de/landtag/aktuelles/data/87854/ thueringer-landtag.de]</ref> and at the latest 61 months after, i.e. at the earliest 21 July 2019 and at the latest 10 November 2019.<ref>[http://www.wahlen.thueringen.de/wahltermine.asp Wahltermine in Th\u00fcringen], auf wahlen.thueringen.de</ref> On 28 August 2018, the [[Cabinet Ramelow|Thuringian Land government]] announced that the election was to take place on 27 October 2019.<ref>[https://www.thueringer-allgemeine.de/politik/landtagswahl-in-thueringen-soll-am-27-oktober-2019-stattfinden-id224551591.html Landtagswahl in Th\u00fcringen soll am 27. Oktober 2019 stattfinden], auf thueringer-allgemeine.de, abgerufen am 28. August 2018.</ref>\n\n==Opinion polls==\n===Graphical summary===\n[[File:2019 Thuringian state election polls.svg|1100x1100px]]\n===Party polling===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;line-height:14px;\"\n|- style=\"height:40px;\"\n! style=\"width:160px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Polling firm\n! style=\"width:125px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Fieldwork date\n! style=\"width:35px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Sample<br>size\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[The Left (Germany)|Linke]]\n! cla