rcentage6    = 5.0%\n| swing6         = {{increase}} 2.5%\n\n<!-- Map -->\n| map_image   = Th\u00fcringen Landtagswahlkarte 2019.svg\n| map_size    = 400px\n| map_caption = Results for the direct mandates.\n\n<!-- Result -->\n| title           = [[List of Ministers-President of Thuringia|Minister-President]]\n| before_election = [[Bodo Ramelow]]\n| before_party    = The Left (Germany)\n| after_election  = [[Thomas Kemmerich]]\n| after_party     = Free Democratic Party (Germany)\n}}\nThe '''2019 Thuringian state election''' was held on 27 October 2019 to elect the members of the 7th [[Landtag of Thuringia]]. The incumbent government was a coalition consisting of [[The Left (Germany)|The Left]], the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democratic Party]] (SPD), and [[Alliance 90/The Greens|The Greens]], led by [[List of Ministers-President of Thuringia|Minister-President]] [[Bodo Ramelow]]. The Left became the largest party for the first time in any German state, but the election resulted in a [[hung parliament]] as the governing coalition fell 4 seats short of an overall majority. As The Left and the far-right [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) together hold a negative majority, no politically realistic majority government exists.\n\nOn 5 February 2020, the Landtag voted to elect the Minister-President. Ramelow was expected to be re-elected to lead a minority government, since the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union]] (CDU) declined to run a candidate, and neither the AfD's candidate nor the [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|Free Democratic Party]] (FDP) leader [[Thomas Kemmerich]] were expected to garner enough votes to win. However, on the third ballot, Kemmerich was unexpectedly elected, winning 45 votes to incumbent Ramelow's 44. The votes for Kemmerich came from the FDP, CDU and, controversially, the AfD. This was the first time the AfD had been involved in the election of a head of government in Germany. This was highly controversial, sparking protest throughout both Thuringia and Germany and condemnation from politicians nationwide, including federal Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], who described it as \"unforgivable\".<ref name=\"BBC-8-2-2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51399445|title=Germany AfD: Thuringia PM quits amid fury over far right|publisher=BBC|date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nUnder intense pressure, Kemmerich announced his resignation just two days later, but remained in office in a caretaker capacity until the Landtag could elect another Minister-President.<ref name=\"BBC-8-2-2020\"></ref> On 4 March, a second vote was held, and Bodo Ramelow was re-elected as Minister-President with the abstentions of the CDU and FDP.<ref name=\"Politico-5-3-20\">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/germanys-thuringia-gets-left-wing-state-premier-in-re-run-vote/|title=Germany\u2019s Thuringia gets left-wing state premier in re-run vote|date=4 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Election date==\nAccording to \u00a7 18 of the ''Thuringian Electoral Law for the Landtag'',<ref>[http://landesrecht.thueringen.de/jportal/portal/t/glw/page/bsthueprod.psml/action/portlets.jw.MainAction?p1=n&eventSubmit_doNavigate=searchInSubtreeTOC&showdoccase=1&doc.hl=0&doc.id=jlr-WahlGTH2012pP18&doc.part=S&toc.poskey=#focuspoint landesrecht.thueringen.de]</ref> the Landtag election must take place on a [[Sunday]] or [[public holiday]] at the earliest 57 months after the beginning of the current parliamentary term on 14 October 2014<ref>Konstituierende Sitzung des 6. Landtags, auf [http://www.thueringer-landtag.de/landtag/aktuelles/data/87854/ thueringer-landtag.de]</ref> and at the latest 61 months after, i.e. at the earliest 21 July 2019 and at the latest 10 November 2019.<ref>[http://www.wahlen.thueringen.de/wahltermine.asp Wahltermine in Th\u00fcringen], auf wahlen.thueringen.de</ref> On 28 August 2018, the [[Cabinet Ramelow|Thuringian Land government]] announced that the election was to take place on 27 October 2019.<ref>[https://www.thueringer-allgemeine.de/politik/landtagswahl-in-thueringen-soll-am-27-oktober-2019-stattfinden-id224551591.html Landtagswahl in Th\u00fcringen soll am 27. Oktober 2019 stattfinden], auf thueringer-allgemeine.de, abgerufen am 28. August 2018.</ref>\n\n==Opinion polls==\n===Graphical summary===\n[[File:2019 Thuringian state election polls.svg|1100x1100px]]\n===Party polling===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;line-height:14px;\"\n|- style=\"height:40px;\"\n! style=\"width:160px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Polling firm\n! style=\"width:125px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Fieldwork date\n! style=\"width:35px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Sample<br>size\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[The Left (Germany)|Linke]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|SPD]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Alternative for Germany|AfD]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Alliance 90/The Greens|Gr\u00fcne]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[National Democratic Party of Germany|NPD]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Free Democratic Party (Germany)|FDP]]\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:40px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Others\n! style=\"width:30px;\" rowspan=\"2\"| Lead\n|-\n! style=\"background:{{Christian Democratic Union of Germany/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{The Left (Germany)/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Social Democratic Party of Germany/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Alternative for Germany/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Alliance 90/The Greens/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{National Democratic Party of Germany/meta/color}};\"|\n! style=\"background:{{Free Democratic Party (Germany)/meta/color}};\"|\n|- style=\"background:#E9E9E9;\"\n| [https://wahlen.thueringen.de/daten