{"title_page": "Chanie Rosenberg", "text_new": "'''Chanie Rosenberg''' (born 1922) is a South African-born artist, former teacher and socialist who is the sister of [[Michael Kidron]], the widow of [[Tony Cliff]], and a founder member of the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] in Britain.<ref>[http://cosmos.ucc.ie/cs1064/jabowen/IPSC/php/authors.php?auid=2365] ''Short biography''</ref>\n\n==Life==\nChanie Rosenberg was born to a Jewish Zionist family in [[South Africa]]. In 1944 she moved to Palestine to live on a kibbutz where she met Yigael Gluckstein, better known under his pen name of [[Tony Cliff]]. After the war she moved to Britain where she is still (at 96) active as a socialist. She worked as a teacher who was active in the [[National Union of Teachers]].<ref>[http://socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=28167] ''Interview with Chanie Rosenberg''</ref> She is also an artist whose sculpture has been exhibited in the [[Royal Academy of Arts]].<ref>[http://resolutereader.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/chanie-rosenberg-fighting-fit-memoir.html]''Review of Fighting Fit''</ref>\n\n==Selected writings==\n*''Education and Society: A rank-and-file pamphlet'' (1968)\n*[https://www.marxists.org/history/etol/writers/rosenberg/1972/xx/education.html ''Education and Revolution: a great experiment in socialist education''] (1972)\n*''Class Size and the Relationship Between Official and Unofficial Action in the NUT'' (1977) \n*''Women and Perestroika'' (1989)\n*''Education under capitalism and socialism'' (1991)\n*''1919: Britain on the Brink of Revolution'' (1995)\n*''Education: Why our children deserve better than New Labour'' (with [[Kevin Ovenden]]) (1999)\n*''Fighting Fit: A Memoir'' (includes an illustrated pamphlet on ''Malevich and Revolution'') (2013)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Ian Birchall]] ''Tony Cliff: A Marxist for his time'' (2011)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marxists.org/history/etol/writers/rosenberg/index.htm Chanie Rosenberg Internet Archive]\n*[http://socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=28167 Interview with Chanie Rosenberg in 2012]\n*[http://resolutereader.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/chanie-rosenberg-fighting-fit-memoir.html Review of Fighting Fit]\n*[http://leftunity.org/david-widgery-dissident-marxist/chanie/ Image of Chanie Rosenberg and Tony Cliff]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenberg, Chanie}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:British political writers]]\n[[Category:British Trotskyists]]\n[[Category:International Socialist Tendency]]\n[[Category:Jewish socialists]]\n[[Category:Revolutionary Communist Party (UK, 1944) members]]\n[[Category:Socialist Workers Party (UK) members]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n", "text_old": "'''Chanie Rosenberg''' (born 1922) is a South African-born artist, former teacher and socialist who is the sister of [[Michael Kidron]], the widow of [[Tony Cliff]], and a founder member of the [[Socialist Workers Party (UK)|Socialist Workers Party]] in Britain.<ref>[http://cosmos.ucc.ie/cs1064/jabowen/IPSC/php/authors.php?auid=2365] ''Short biography''</ref>\n\n==Life==\nChanie Rosenberg was born to a Jewish Zionist family in [[South Africa]]. In 1944 she moved to Palestine to live on a kibbutz where she met Yigael Gluckstein, better known under his pen name of [[Tony Cliff]]. After the war she moved to Britain where she is still (at 96) active as a socialist. She worked as a teacher who was active in the [[National Union of Teachers]].<ref>[http://socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=28167] ''Interview with Chanie Rosenberg''</ref> She is also an artist whose sculpture has been exhibited in the [[Royal Academy of Arts]].<ref> [http://resolutereader.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/chanie-rosenberg-fighting-fit-memoir.html]''Review of Fighting Fit''</ref>\n\n==Selected writings==\n*''Education and Society: A rank-and-file pamphlet'' (1968)\n*[https://www.marxists.org/history/etol/writers/rosenberg/1972/xx/education.html ''Education and Revolution: a great experiment in socialist education''] (1972)\n*''Class Size and the Relationship Between Official and Unofficial Action in the NUT'' (1977) \n*''Women and Perestroika'' (1989)\n*''Education under capitalism and socialism'' (1991)\n*''1919: Britain on the Brink of Revolution'' (1995)\n*''Education: Why our children deserve better than New Labour'' (with [[Kevin Ovenden]]) (1999)\n*''Fighting Fit: A Memoir'' (includes an illustrated pamphlet on ''Malevich and Revolution'') (2013)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Ian Birchall]] ''Tony Cliff: A Marxist for his time'' (2011)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marxists.org/history/etol/writers/rosenberg/index.htm Chanie Rosenberg Internet Archive]\n*[http://socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=28167 Interview with Chanie Rosenberg in 2012]\n*[http://resolutereader.blogspot.co.uk/2013/10/chanie-rosenberg-fighting-fit-memoir.html Review of Fighting Fit]\n*[http://leftunity.org/david-widgery-dissident-marxist/chanie/ Image of Chanie Rosenberg and Tony Cliff]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rosenberg, Chanie}}\n[[Category:1922 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British Jewish writers]]\n[[Category:British political writers]]\n[[Category:British Trotskyists]]\n[[Category:International Socialist Tendency]]\n[[Category:Jewish socialists]]\n[[Category:Revolutionary Communist Party (UK, 1944) members]]\n[[Category:Socialist Workers Party (UK) members]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chanie_Rosenberg"}
{"title_page": "Cesare Alpini", "text_new": "'''Cesare Alpini''' (born 9 May 1956) is an Italian art historian. Born in [[Crema, Lombardy]], he specialises in art from that city and [[Lombardy]] more widely. He is most notable for his contributions to scholarship on [[Giovanni Battista Lucini]] (on whom he is considered the main expert)<ref>{{DBI|nome=Giovan Battista Lucini|name=giovan-battista-lucini|author=Micaela Mander|volume=66|year=2007|access-date=22 August 2014}}</ref> and [[Gian Giacomo Barbelli]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://formesettanta.wordpress.com/tag/cesare-alpini/|title=Gian Giacomo Barbelli e il barocco cremasco|language=it|access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref> He has collaborated on several art exhibitions held in Crema, including ''Pittura sacra a Crema dal '400 al '700'' (1992),<ref>{{Cite news|title= Pittura sacra del '400 in \"vetrina\" a Crema|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1992/giugno/17/pittura_sacra_del_400_vetrina_co_0_92061717444.shtml|publisher= [[Corriere della Sera]]|date= 17 June 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101000000/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1992/giugno/17/pittura_sacra_del_400_vetrina_co_0_92061717444.shtml|access-date = 29 March 2015|archive-date=2016-01-01|language=it}}</ref> ''L'estro e la realt\u00e0'' (1997),<ref name= insulafulcheria>{{cite web|url=http://www.comune.crema.cr.it/sviluppo/public/upload/File/FDMuseo/Insula_Fulcheria_XXXVII_2008/Insula_vol_B/345_352_gli_autori.pdf|title='Alpini Cesare' in ''Insula Fulcheria'', XXXVII B, Crema, 2008, pp. 345|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514212513/http://www.comune.crema.cr.it/sviluppo/public/upload/File/FDMuseo/Insula_Fulcheria_XXXVII_2008/Insula_vol_B/345_352_gli_autori.pdf|archive-date=2014-05-14|language=it}}</ref> ''Officina Veneziana ''(2002) and ''Luigi Manini'' (2007).<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.exibart.com/profilo/autoriv2/persona_view.asp?id=148484|title= Cesare Alpini |access-date= 8 January 2014|language=it}}</ref>\n\n== Works (in Italian) ==\n=== Monographs===\n* ''Giovan Battista Lucini: 1639-1686'', Crema, 1987.\n* ''La Basilica di Santa Maria della Croce a Crema'', Silvana editoriale, 1990.\n* ''Giovanni da Monte. Un pittore da Crema all'Europa'', Bolis, 1996.\n* with Goffredo Colombani e Chiara Coppa, ''Carlo Casanova. L'ultimo dei romantici'', Ed. d'arte Severgnini, 2004.\n\n=== Essays in collections===\n* 'Il Settecento di terraferma', in Federico Zeri (editor), ''Pinacoteca di Brera. Scuola veneta'', Electa, 1990.\n* 'I pittori e le botteghe artistiche in Crema nei secoli del Dominio Veneziano', in Filippo Pedrocco and Fabrizio Magani (editors), ''Officina veneziana. Maestri e botteghe nella Venezia del Settecento'', Skira, 2002, {{ISBN|88-8491-220-2}}.\n* Gaia Piccarolo and Giuliana Ricci (editors), ''Luigi Manini (1848-1936)'', Skira, 2007, {{ISBN|97888-3660888-1}}.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web|url=https://openlibrary.org/works/OL190233A|title=Works by Cesara Alpini on OpenLibrary}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alpini, Cesare}}\n[[Category:Italian art historians]]\n[[Category:People from Crema, Lombardy]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n", "text_old": "'''Cesare Alpini''' (born 9 May 1956) is an Italian art historian. Born in [[Crema, Lombardy]], he specialises in art from that city and [[Lombardy]] more widely. He is most notable for his contributions to scholarship on [[Giovanni Battista Lucini]] (on whom he is considered the main expert)<ref>{{DBI|nome=Giovan Battista Lucini|name=giovan-battista-lucini|author=Micaela Mander|volume=66|year=2007|access-date=22 August 2014}}</ref> and [[Gian Giacomo Barbelli]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://formesettanta.wordpress.com/tag/cesare-alpini/|title=Gian Giacomo Barbelli e il barocco cremasco|language=it|access-date=25 July 2014}}</ref>. He has collaborated on several art exhibitions held in Crema, including ''Pittura sacra a Crema dal '400 al '700'' (1992)<ref>{{Cite news|title= Pittura sacra del '400 in \"vetrina\" a Crema|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1992/giugno/17/pittura_sacra_del_400_vetrina_co_0_92061717444.shtml|publisher= [[Corriere della Sera]]|date= 17 June 1992|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160101000000/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1992/giugno/17/pittura_sacra_del_400_vetrina_co_0_92061717444.shtml|access-date = 29 March 2015|archive-date=2016-01-01|language=it}}</ref>, ''L'estro e la realt\u00e0'' (1997)<ref name= insulafulcheria>{{cite web|url=http://www.comune.crema.cr.it/sviluppo/public/upload/File/FDMuseo/Insula_Fulcheria_XXXVII_2008/Insula_vol_B/345_352_gli_autori.pdf|title='Alpini Cesare' in ''Insula Fulcheria'', XXXVII B, Crema, 2008, pp. 345|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140514212513/http://www.comune.crema.cr.it/sviluppo/public/upload/File/FDMuseo/Insula_Fulcheria_XXXVII_2008/Insula_vol_B/345_352_gli_autori.pdf|archive-date=2014-05-14|language=it}}</ref>, ''Officina Veneziana ''(2002) and ''Luigi Manini'' (2007)<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.exibart.com/profilo/autoriv2/persona_view.asp?id=148484|title= Cesare Alpini |access-date= 8 January 2014|language=it}}</ref>.\n\n== Works (in Italian) ==\n=== Monographs===\n* ''Giovan Battista Lucini: 1639-1686'', Crema, 1987.\n* ''La Basilica di Santa Maria della Croce a Crema'', Silvana editoriale, 1990.\n* ''Giovanni da Monte. Un pittore da Crema all'Europa'', Bolis, 1996.\n* with Goffredo Colombani e Chiara Coppa, ''Carlo Casanova. L'ultimo dei romantici'', Ed. d'arte Severgnini, 2004.\n\n=== Essays in collections===\n* 'Il Settecento di terraferma', in Federico Zeri (editor), ''Pinacoteca di Brera. Scuola veneta'', Electa, 1990.\n* 'I pittori e le botteghe artistiche in Crema nei secoli del Dominio Veneziano', in Filippo Pedrocco and Fabrizio Magani (editors), ''Officina veneziana. Maestri e botteghe nella Venezia del Settecento'', Skira, 2002, {{ISBN|88-8491-220-2}}.\n* Gaia Piccarolo and Giuliana Ricci (editors), ''Luigi Manini (1848-1936)'', Skira, 2007, {{ISBN|97888-3660888-1}}.\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Cite web|url=https://openlibrary.org/works/OL190233A|title=Works by Cesara Alpini on OpenLibrary}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alpini, Cesare}}\n[[category:Italian art historians]]\n[[category:People from Crema, Lombardy]]\n[[category:Living people]]\n[[category:1956 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cesare_Alpini"}
{"title_page": "Deque Systems", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2019}}{{Infobox company\n| logo=Deque_Systems_Logo.png\n| logo_size=200px\n| name     = Deque Systems\n| type     = [[Private Company]]\n| location         = [[Herndon, VA]]\n| key_people       = {{Unbulleted list\n  |Preety Kumar ([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])\n}}\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| industry         = [[Web accessibility|Web Accessibility]]\n| homepage         = {{Url |https://www.deque.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Deque Systems''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|k|j|u\u02d0}} {{respell|DEE|kew}}) is a digital accessibility company based in [[Herndon, Virginia]] with additional offices in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thewholebraingroup.com/deque-sets-labs-office-ann-arbor/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102055316/http://www.thewholebraingroup.com/deque-sets-labs-office-ann-arbor/ |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and  [[Madhapur|Kavuri Hills Madhapur, India]]. The company was started in 1999 and produces accessibility software in addition to offering accessibility consulting services.\n\nThe CEO of Deque Systems is Preety Kumar.<ref>http://www.washingtonexec.com/2012/07/deque-systems-software-makes-websites-more-accessible/</ref>\n\n==Products==\nDeque tools, services and training are used to achieve compliance in support of the [[World Wide Web Consortium|W3C]]'s [[Web Content Accessibility Guidelines]],<ref>https://www.w3.org/WAI/ER/tools/</ref> the [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|Americans with Disabilities Act]] and [[Section 508 Amendment to the Rehabilitation Act of 1973|Section 508]].\n\n'''WorldSpace''' is an enterprise-level toolkit for automated web and native mobile accessibility testing and monitoring of websites.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wiki.state.ma.us/confluence/display/assistivetechnologygroup/Deque+-+Worldspace+Enterprise |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102080210/https://wiki.state.ma.us/confluence/display/assistivetechnologygroup/Deque+-+Worldspace+Enterprise |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[https://www.deque.com/axe/ '''axe'''] is a free testing app and API for testing web pages, [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] applications for web accessibility errors. <ref>https://wptavern.com/axe-an-open-source-javascript-library-for-automating-accessibility-testing</ref> <ref>https://www.windowscentral.com/microsoft-and-deque-make-accessibility-easy-millions-developers</ref>\n\n'''Amaze''' is a tool which produces server-based accessibility overlays in order to render web pages accessible for users with disabilities.\n\n'''Deque University''' is a collection of online accessibility training courses covering a range of topics from introductory level to expert-level [[International Association of Accessibility Professionals]] CPACC. <ref>https://www.accessibilityassociation.org/cpacccertification</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Web accessibility}}\n\n[[Category:Technology companies of the United States]]\n\n\n{{Tech-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2019}}{{Infobox company\n| logo=Deque_Systems_Logo.png\n| logo_size=200px\n| name     = Deque Systems\n| type     = [[Private Company]]\n| location         = [[Herndon, VA]]\n| key_people       = {{Unbulleted list\n  |Preety Kumar ([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])\n}}\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| industry         = [[Web accessibility|Web Accessibility]]\n| homepage         = {{Url |https://www.deque.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Deque Systems''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|i\u02d0|k|j|u\u02d0}} {{respell|DEE|kew}}) is a digital accessibility company based in [[Herndon, Virginia]] with additional offices in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.thewholebraingroup.com/deque-sets-labs-office-ann-arbor/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102055316/http://www.thewholebraingroup.com/deque-sets-labs-office-ann-arbor/ |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and [[Secunderabad|Secunderabad, India]]. The company was started in 1999 and produces accessibility software in addition to offering accessibility consulting services.\n\nThe CEO of Deque Systems is Preety Kumar.<ref>http://www.washingtonexec.com/2012/07/deque-systems-software-makes-websites-more-accessible/</ref>\n\n==Products==\nDeque tools, services and training are used to achieve compliance in support of the [[World Wide Web Consortium|W3C]]'s [[Web Content Accessibility Guidelines]],<ref>https://www.w3.org/WAI/ER/tools/</ref> the [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|Americans with Disabilities Act]] and [[Section 508 Amendment to the Rehabilitation Act of 1973|Section 508]].\n\n'''WorldSpace''' is an enterprise-level toolkit for automated web and native mobile accessibility testing and monitoring of websites.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://wiki.state.ma.us/confluence/display/assistivetechnologygroup/Deque+-+Worldspace+Enterprise |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-10-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102080210/https://wiki.state.ma.us/confluence/display/assistivetechnologygroup/Deque+-+Worldspace+Enterprise |archive-date=2013-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n[https://www.deque.com/axe/ '''axe'''] is a free testing app and API for testing web pages, [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] applications for web accessibility errors. <ref>https://wptavern.com/axe-an-open-source-javascript-library-for-automating-accessibility-testing</ref> <ref>https://www.windowscentral.com/microsoft-and-deque-make-accessibility-easy-millions-developers</ref>\n\n'''Amaze''' is a tool which produces server-based accessibility overlays in order to render web pages accessible for users with disabilities.\n\n'''Deque University''' is a collection of online accessibility training courses covering a range of topics from introductory level to expert-level [[International Association of Accessibility Professionals]] CPACC. <ref>https://www.accessibilityassociation.org/cpacccertification</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Web accessibility}}\n\n[[Category:Technology companies of the United States]]\n\n\n{{Tech-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Arup.Upopadhyay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Deque india office has shifted from Secundrabad to Madhapur location.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deque_Systems"}
{"title_page": "Decoration and Glass", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Decoration.and.glass.jpg|thumb|Cover of the first issue of ''Decoration and Glass'', May 1934]]\n\n'''''Decoration and Glass''''', was an English language trade journal, issued from 1935 to 1949, and published in [[Sydney, New South Wales|Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].\n\n== History ==\n'''''Decoration and Glass : journal for home builders, architects and decorators''''' was the official journal of the Australian Glass Manufacturers Company. While the earliest edition of Decoration and Glass was issued May 1935, the journal was published simply as '''''Glass''''' between 1934 and 1935.<ref name=\"DAAO\">{{cite web |title=Don Angus, artist |url=https://www.daao.org.au/bio/don-angus/references/ |website=Design and Art Australia Online |publisher=DAAO |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The earliest editors of the journal were Walter Glover, as managing editor and publisher, and Don Angus, as art director. Angus later established himself as a commercial artist in his own right, operating out of a studio in Hunter Street Sydney, and later became the vice-president of the Australian Commercial and Industrial Artists Association in Victoria.<ref name=\"DAAO\"/> While Glover, was the same Walter Frederick Glover, who went on to some degree of infamy as the champion of the art of [[Rosaleen Norton]], and the publisher of a book of her art, resulting in his being charged by police with the production of an obscene publication.<ref name=\"Norton\">{{cite news |title=Artist's sex book called fantasitic |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article168011472 |accessdate=26 June 2018 |work=Truth}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Obscene Art Book Results In Fine |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18356219 |accessdate=26 June 2018 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=35,921}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Editor of ''Glass'' Meets with Mishap |journal=Glass |date=1 January 1935 |issue=1 Jan. 1935 |pages=35 |url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-641377952/view?partId=nla.obj-641382121#page/n36/mode/1up |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAppearing directly after the height of the Great Depression in Australia, the Journal's focus on colourful interior decoration, decorative and ornamental architecture and glass work was considered progressive for its time.<ref name=\"DAAO\"/> In addition to reflecting the styles and fashions of the period, the journal also reflected the increasing individual wealth and home ownership of the time, as Australia's economy slowly recovered.<ref name=\"Morley\">{{cite web |last1=Morley |first1=Sarah |title=Decoration and Glass Magazine |url=http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/stories/decoration-and-glass-magazine |website=State Library of NSW |accessdate=26 June 2018|date=2017-07-04 }}</ref>\n\n== Digitisation ==\n''Decoration and glass'' has been digitised as part of the Digitised newspapers and more<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/?q|title=Digitised newspapers and more|last=|first=|date=|website=Trove|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> in [[Trove]] at the [[National Library of Australia]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}<!--does not appear to be digitised, eg at https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-347231133-->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of magazines in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-347231133 ''Decoration and glass''] at [[Trove]]\n\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of Sydney]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of Australia]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Sydney]]\n\n\n{{Australia-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Decoration.and.glass.jpg|thumb|Cover of the first issue of ''Decoration and Glass'', May 1934]]\n\n'''''Decoration and Glass''''', was an English language trade journal, issued from 1935 to 1949, and published in [[Sydney, New South Wales|Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], [[Australia]].\n\n== History ==\n'''''Decoration and Glass : journal for home builders, architects and decorators''''' was the official journal of the Australian Glass Manufacturers Company. While the earliest edition of Decoration and Glass was issued May 1935, the journal was published simply as '''''Glass''''' between 1934 and 1935.<ref name=\"DAAO\">{{cite web |title=Don Angus, artist |url=https://www.daao.org.au/bio/don-angus/references/ |website=Design and Art Australia Online |publisher=DAAO |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref> The earliest editors of the journal were Walter Glover, as managing editor and publisher, and Don Angus, as art director. Angus later established himself as a commercial artist in his own right, operating out of a studio in Hunter Street Sydney, and later became the vice-president of the Australian Commercial and Industrial Artists Association in Victoria.<ref name=\"DAAO\"/> While Glover, was the same Walter Frederick Glover, who went on to some degree of infamy as the champion of the art of [[Rosaleen Norton]], and the publisher of a book of her art, resulting in his being charged by police with the production of an obscene publication.<ref name=\"Norton\">{{cite news |title=Artist's sex book called fantasitic |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article168011472 |accessdate=26 June 2018 |work=Truth}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Obscene Art Book Results In Fine |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18356219 |accessdate=26 June 2018 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |issue=35,921}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Editor of ''Glass'' Meets with Mishap |journal=Glass |date=1 January 1935 |issue=1 Jan. 1935 |pages=35 |url=https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-641377952/view?partId=nla.obj-641382121#page/n36/mode/1up |accessdate=26 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nAppearing directly after the height of the Great Depression in Australia, the Journal's focus on colourful interior decoration, decorative and ornamental architecture and glass work was considered progressive for its time.<ref name=\"DAAO\"/> In addition to reflecting the styles and fashions of the period, the journal also reflected the increasing individual wealth and home ownership of the time, as Australia's economy slowly recovered.<ref name=\"Morley\">{{cite web |last1=Morley |first1=Sarah |title=Decoration and Glass Magazine |url=http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/stories/decoration-and-glass-magazine |website=State Library of NSW |accessdate=26 June 2018|date=2017-07-04 }}</ref>\n\n== Digitisation ==\n''Decoration and glass'' has been digitised as part of the Digitised newspapers and more<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/?q|title=Digitised newspapers and more|last=|first=|date=|website=Trove|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> in Trove at the [[National Library of Australia]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}<!--does not appear to be digitised, eg at https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-347231133-->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of magazines in Australia]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://nla.gov.au/nla.obj-347231133 ''Decoration and glass''] at [[Trove]]\n\n[[Category:Defunct newspapers of Sydney]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of Australia]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Sydney]]\n\n\n{{Australia-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ktweeddale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDigitisation:minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoration_and_Glass"}
